   =20
      Tether lending
   =20
 =20

I know I say this a lot but I really can=E2=80=99t stress enough what a goo=
d business Tether, the big stablecoin issuer, is. It is an=C2=A0unregulated=
 bank that does not pay interest, rates are going up, and its depositor bas=
e is quite stable. As of the end of June,  Tether reported assets of about =
$86.5 billion, a majority of it in US Treasury bills, to back about $83.2 b=
illion of Tethers. That=E2=80=99s up slightly from  the previous quarter: I=
n last year=E2=80=99s crypto winter there was a bit of a run on Tether, but=
 not that much, and it has recovered well; crypto people continue to want t=
o keep their money in Tether.
Anyway, if you are in charge of Tether, you shouldn=E2=80=99t have to worry=
 about run risk. Tether invests in mostly short-term safe stuff, and short-=
term safe stuff pays a lot of interest now.=C2=A0Just investing Tether=E2=
=80=99s pot of money in overnight loans secured by US Treasuries at the Sec=
ured Overnight Financing Rate would get you a yield of about 5.3%, or about=
 $4.6 billion a year, absolutely risk-free and with essentially no expenses=
.
  [1]
=C2=A0If people come in with Tethers looking to get dollars back, you can j=
ust give them the dollars; your investments are short-term and liquid. Phen=
omenal business.
What this means is that if you are in charge of Tether and someone shows up=
 at your office to pitch you on a clever investment that will get you a hig=
her return with only a little risk, you should put your fingers in your ear=
s and scream =E2=80=9CNO=E2=80=9D and kick them out of your office. You can=
 make billions of dollars of pure profit taking=C2=A0no=C2=A0risk! No credi=
t risk (buy Treasuries), no duration risk (buy very short-dated Treasuries)=
, no liquidity risk (easily sell your Treasuries if anyone withdraws Tether=
s), no nothing, 5% interest.
This sort of thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0where to put the money =E2=80=94=C2=A0can=
 be an existential problem for real banks! We have   talked about how Silic=
on Valley Bank needed to take investment risk to make enough money to run i=
ts business, so it put money into long-term Treasuries thinking they were s=
afe, and then there was a run on the bank and SVB collapsed. I feel for the=
m; they had to take risks to make money. Tether does not! Not at all, not a=
 teeny bit; if Tether loaned $100 to Apple Inc. for a month that would be s=
lightly irrational.
And yet Tether=E2=80=99s disclosed balance sheet is=C2=A0not, entirely, the=
 safest stuff you can imagine. At the Wall Street Journal,  Jonathan Weil r=
eports:

Tether Holdings resumed lending out its own stablecoins to customers, less =
than a year after it said it would wind down the practice.
The cryptocurrency issuer in its latest quarterly financial update said its=
 assets included $5.5 billion of loans as of June 30, up from $5.3 billion =
a quarter earlier. A company spokeswoman confirmed that Tether made new loa=
ns.
The company, which is incorporated in the British Virgin Islands, calls the=
m secured loans and discloses little about the borrowers or the collateral =
accepted. The loans are issued and denominated in the company=E2=80=99s tet=
her tokens. =E2=80=A6
The resumption of lending is a shift from December 2022, when the company s=
aid it would reduce its secured loans to zero during 2023. =E2=80=9CDuring =
the second quarter of 2023, we received a few short-term loan requests from=
 clients with whom we have cultivated longstanding relationships, and we ma=
de the decision to accommodate these requests,=E2=80=9D Tether Holdings spo=
keswoman Alex Welch said.
She said loans would be eliminated by 2024. She said the company=E2=80=99s =
aim =E2=80=9Cis to prevent any significant depletion of our customers=E2=80=
=99 liquidity or the need for them to sell their collateral at potentially =
unfavorable prices, which could result in losses.=E2=80=9D
Welch declined to explain why the company=E2=80=99s customers might have ne=
eded to sell their collateral at unfavorable prices, or whether Tether Hold=
ings made new loans this year to help customers avoid defaulting on existin=
g loans.=C2=A0

The point I made above is that there is no financial reason for Tether to=
=C2=A0want=C2=A0these loans. Everyone involved in Tether can get dynastical=
ly wealthy and live an easy life by putting all the money in Treasury bills=
.
Tether=E2=80=99s spokeswoman is making the same point here: Tether isn=E2=
=80=99t making these loans because=C2=A0it=C2=A0wants to, because it thinks=
 they are a good financial decision for Tether. Tether is making these loan=
s to=C2=A0support its borrowers. Somebody out there =E2=80=94=C2=A0crypto e=
xchanges or trading firms, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0has some collateral (presuma=
bly volatile cryptocurrencies) and wants to borrow dollars (in the form of =
Tethers), and Tether Holdings is the cheapest and most available lender the=
y can find. Somebody in crypto needs money to buy (or keep holding onto) th=
eir crypto, and Tether will provide the money, secured by the crypto, not b=
ecause that=E2=80=99s a good deal for Tether but because Tether is being a =
good citizen of the crypto ecosystem and supporting its counterparties.
Tether=E2=80=99s borrowers are big crypto investors looking to get financin=
g for their crypto collateral, and if they ran out of liquidity they would =
need =E2=80=9Cto sell their collateral at potentially unfavorable prices, w=
hich could result in losses.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0If big crypto firms get margin c=
alls and have to dump their assets, that will drive down the prices of cryp=
to assets. Lending them money is not just good for them, it=E2=80=99s good =
for the crypto ecosystem broadly: It prevents fire sales that might drive d=
own prices.
We have   talked about Tether=E2=80=99s lending activity before. One common=
 form of crypto-skeptical conspiracy theory in recent years goes something =
like this: =E2=80=9CTether is a form of self-sustaining fractional reserve =
banking for crypto, and it dynamically prints Tethers in order to prop up c=
rypto prices. At the margin, cryptocurrencies are not purchased by real peo=
ple putting new dollars into the crypto system, but by crypto hedge funds b=
uying crypto using freshly printed Tethers.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
This is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0kind of =E2=80=A6 a Tether spokeswoman =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0saying =E2=80=A6=C2=A0that?=C2=A0

