   =20
      AT1s
   =20
 =20

 Sure:

Some investors are bidding up legal claims on Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s addit=
ional-tier 1 debt in a bet that they can recover some value from the bonds =
that were wiped out during the UBS Group AG takeover.
The trading desk at Cantor Fitzgerald has circulated an offer to buy some o=
f the claims at 9.5 cents on the dollar each, according to people familiar =
with the matter who asked not to be identified. That=E2=80=99s up from arou=
nd 3 to 4 cents in mid-August, they said.
It=E2=80=99s a sign that some money managers are taking wagers on a settlem=
ent with Swiss authorities over the controversial decision to make Credit S=
uisse=E2=80=99s risky AT1 bonds worthless. Investors in the AT1 claims are =
targeting a settlement of around 15 cents, said one person who is part of o=
ne of the lawsuits. Another person involved with one of the large bondholde=
r groups suing Swiss authorities said they would look for a significantly h=
igher payout than that.

Without getting too much into the legal details here, there are  two basic =
ways to think about Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s AT1s:
=09The AT1s were bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0risky bonds, but bonds =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and should have had priority over Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s stock. When UB=
S Group AG  took over Credit Suisse, it paid Credit Suisse shareholders som=
ething (roughly 0.76 Swiss francs worth of UBS stock), but it paid the AT1 =
holders nothing (their bonds got canceled). This was an outrage, a violatio=
n of the normal priority of bondholders; the AT1s should have been repaid i=
n full before shareholders got anything.=09The AT1s were a particular sort =
of capital security, and they were designed explicitly to go to zero=C2=A0b=
efore the stock did:=C2=A0If Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s common equity capital =
ratio fell below 7% (that is, if its common stock was still valuable, but t=
oo low relative to its assets), then the AT1s would be triggered and be wri=
tten off entirely. As a matter of regulatory capital accounting, that didn=
=E2=80=99t happen, which is what brought on these lawsuits, but as a rough =
intuitive economic matter it is absolutely the case that the AT1s were supp=
osed to go to zero before the stock did.

These are pretty absolute views, though, and you could imagine a compromise=
. One rough compromise might be =E2=80=9Cehhhhhh the AT1s should be treated=
 more or less like stock=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0not absolutely prior to st=
ock (like in View 1), and not absolutely behind stock (like in View 2), but=
 just parallel to stock. That is a pretty normal approach; other banks=C2=
=A0have AT1 instruments that=C2=A0convert into stock=C2=A0when the bank run=
s into trouble, instead of=C2=A0being written down to zero. We  talked the =
other day about how UBS is going out to market more AT1 instruments (to rep=
lace the zeroed Credit Suisse ones!), and to make this more palatable it is=
 considering =E2=80=9Creplacing UBS=E2=80=99s AT1 bonds, which are designed=
 to be written down in the event the bank runs into trouble, with versions =
of the security that would be converted into equity.=E2=80=9D
Probably doing that to the old Credit Suisse AT1s, retroactively, would be =
rough justice? Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s shareholders got, I don=E2=80=99t kn=
ow, depends how you count, somewhere between 1 and 40 cents on the dollar f=
or their shares. (The agreed CHF 0.76 price was =E2=80=9C 99% lower than Cr=
edit Suisse's peak share price,=E2=80=9D but only 60% lower than its most r=
ecent closing price.) Giving its AT1 holders 15 cents or so seems=C2=A0fine=
.

