   =20
      NFT Stuff
   =20
 =20

One way to think about crypto is that it often applies infinitely scalable =
technology to ideas that kind of only work once. So in the early days of Bi=
tcoin, a lot of people, including me, thought there was a logical flaw at i=
ts heart: Bitcoin was just a ledger maintained by some open-source code, an=
d if it ever got valuable there was nothing to stop anyone else from clonin=
g it and printing many more quasi-Bitcoins that had the same properties and=
, therefore, the same value as actual Bitcoins. This easy clonability would=
 keep a lid on Bitcoin prices. This was totally wrong! In fact a lot of peo=
ple=C2=A0did=C2=A0make Bitcoin clones, and a few of them ended up being wor=
th, you know, two or three orders of magnitude less than Bitcoin, and the r=
est ended up being worth nothing. There were powerful network effects to be=
ing the original thing, and while it was easy to copy the technical propert=
ies of that thing, the value was not in the technical properties.
Non-fungible tokens have a similar story, but much more so. I do not fully =
understand the appeal of, like, Bored Ape Yacht Club. But it=E2=80=99s some=
thing like:
=09There is a limited collection of digital images of apes, each of which i=
s associated with a numbered crypto token.=09You can buy one of the numbere=
d tokens and then you =E2=80=9Cown,=E2=80=9D in some not-really-worth-think=
ing-about way, the associated image of an ape.=09You can use the ape as you=
r Twitter profile picture,
  [5]
=C2=A0and other people who also =E2=80=9Cown=E2=80=9D apes can see your pro=
file picture and be like =E2=80=9Cooh, you own an ape too, cool cool.=E2=80=
=9D=09Of course anyone can use the ape as their Twitter profile picture =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0buying the token and downloading the digital image are entirely=
 separate transactions =E2=80=94=C2=A0but to the people in the club=C2=A0th=
ose=C2=A0people will look like phonies and poseurs; to be in the club you n=
eed not just the picture but the token.=09Maybe also you like the picture o=
f the ape? You like the aesthetic? It=E2=80=99s like buying a cool article =
of clothing or bag or whatever; you feel good wearing it (as your Twitter p=
rofile picture) and other people in the know also think you are cool.=09The=
 club can have real-life meetups or whatever, where owning the token is you=
r admissions ticket.=09Also other people might want these benefits, the sup=
ply of apes is limited, and maybe you can buy an ape and then sell it to so=
meone else for more money and get rich quick.=09Celebrities and influencers=
 can be enticed into this whole thing, and if they go on TV saying =E2=80=
=9CI own a Bored Ape and I love it, look how bored it is=E2=80=9D maybe the=
 price of your ape will go up.=09Etc.

It=E2=80=99s a combination of quasi-art collection and quasi-club membershi=
p and very 2021 crypto price speculation.
When I put it like that I feel like:
=09Maybe it=E2=80=99s plausible? Not my thing, exactly, but I can see how s=
omeone might want this set of features.=09If it=E2=80=99s plausible, it=E2=
=80=99s plausible=C2=A0more than once. Some people might appreciate the aes=
thetics of the pictures of apes, and want to be in a club with the other ap=
e people; other people might prefer the aesthetics of pictures of cats, and=
 want to be in a club with other cat people.=09It=E2=80=99s not plausible=
=C2=A0that many times? Like you might want to be in a club, or two clubs, o=
r three clubs, and I might want to be in a different club from the clubs yo=
u are in. But only so many people want to be in crypto-y clubs at all, and =
if you do, you probably want to be in clubs that other people are in; there=
 are network effects, and only so many clubs can be valuable and desirable.=
 The mechanics of how some NFT clubs become cool and others don=E2=80=99t a=
re mysterious to me, but some such mechanics have to exist.=09It is trivial=
ly easy and free to create new clubs =E2=80=94=C2=A0to make a new NFT colle=
ction, generate 10,000 ugly images and sell them online =E2=80=94=C2=A0and =
for a while everyone did.=C2=A0=09At the very peak of the bubble, people wo=
uld speculate on any of those (you never know which will take off!), but 99=
% of them will go nowhere.

Anyway here is a very funny  report on the state of NFTs:

A report by dappGambl based on data provided by NFT Scan and CoinMarketCap =
indicated that 95% of non-fungible tokens were effectively worthless. Out o=
f 73,257 NFT collections, 69,795 of them had a market cap of zero ether. =
=E2=80=A6
"This daunting reality should serve as a sobering check on the euphoria tha=
t has often surrounded the NFT space," the researchers said. "Amid stories =
of digital art pieces selling for millions and overnight success stories, i=
t is easy to overlook the fact that the market is fraught with pitfalls and=
 potential losses.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
"It becomes clear that a significant portion of the NFT market is character=
ized by speculative and hopeful pricing strategies that are far removed fro=
m the actual trading history of these assets," the researchers said.

They=E2=80=99re not assets! They=E2=80=99re a joke that was funny once, twi=
ce, maybe a thousand times, but good lord not 73,000 times, come on.=C2=A0
We   talked the other day about the modern history of art pranks, art that =
was designed not to look pretty but to convey that a collector was cool and=
 in on the joke. I wrote:
And then non-fungible tokens were invented to sort of mass-produce this eff=
ect for the internet age. This should not work: Pretty pictures lost their =
edge in the art world because they became too easy to mass-produce, and now=
 being-in-on-a-dumb-stunt has also become easy to mass-produce, and it too =
has, I think, lost its edge. For like seven minutes in 2021, you could say =
=E2=80=9Cgive me money and I will give you a receipt for nothing" and peopl=
e would be like =E2=80=9Coh that=E2=80=99s a cool joke, here=E2=80=99s the =
money=E2=80=9D and feel good and sophisticated, but that was very easy to d=
o, so everyone did, so that market was saturated and it is, I insist, no lo=
nger cool.
So saturated! So not cool.

