      Don=E2=80=99t put it in email, except this one
   =20
 =20

Last Thursday  we discussed a corporate compliance dilemma, which is:
=09Sometimes companies do aggressive things.=09They do not want anyone sayi=
ng anything embarrassing about those things in email: If you are doing an a=
ggressive thing, you want to characterize it very carefully in all of your =
written descriptions. You do not want to create bad evidence for regulators=
 to second-guess what you did.=09People will mess that up.=09The companies =
will want to train people not to mess up; they will want to tell them thing=
s like =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t talk about =E2=80=98crushing the competition=
=E2=80=99 in email.=E2=80=9D=09But that training=C2=A0itself=C2=A0creates b=
ad evidence: Now the regulators have the slide you showed everyone saying =
=E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t talk about =E2=80=98crushing the competition=E2=80=
=99 in email,=E2=80=9D which suggests that you are going around crushing th=
e competition with a guilty conscience.

I proposed that the solution was to separate the aggressive acts from the t=
raining. =E2=80=9CReally this stuff should be taught in college,=E2=80=9D I=
 wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cso that every company can wash its hands of it.=E2=80=
=9D Colleges tell future corporate employees what not to put in email, so t=
he corporations can do aggressive stuff without creating bad evidence, and =
without having to create their own =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t create bad eviden=
ce=E2=80=9D training materials that will themselves be bad evidence.
I really do think that this sort of separation is a good solution, but of c=
ourse I was kidding about doing it in college. Nobody remembers college; it=
 would never work.
