a319a23cB96a82afa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> two basic ways</a> to think about Credit Suisse=
=E2=80=99s AT1s:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The AT1s were bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0ri=
sky bonds, but bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0and should have had priority over Credi=
t Suisse=E2=80=99s stock. When UBS Group AG  took over Credit Suisse, it pa=
id Credit Suisse shareholders something (roughly 0.76 Swiss francs worth of=
 UBS stock), but it paid the AT1 holders nothing (their bonds got canceled)=
. This was an outrage, a violation of the normal priority of bondholders; t=
he AT1s should have been repaid in full before shareholders got anything.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The AT1s were a particular sort of =
capital security, and they were designed explicitly to go to zero=C2=A0<em>=
before the stock did:=C2=A0</em>If Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s common equity ca=
pital ratio fell below 7% (that is, if its common stock was still valuable,=
 but too low relative to its assets), then the AT1s would be triggered and =
be written off entirely. As a matter of regulatory capital accounting, that=
 didn=E2=80=99t happen, which is what brought on these lawsuits, but as a r=
ough intuitive economic matter it is absolutely the case that the AT1s were=
 supposed to go to zero before the stock did.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These are pretty absolute views, though, and y=
ou could imagine a compromise. One rough compromise might be =E2=80=9Cehhhh=
hh the AT1s should be treated more or less like stock=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0not absolutely prior to stock (like in View 1), and not absolutely behin=
d stock (like in View 2), but just parallel to stock. That is a pretty norm=
al approach; other banks=C2=A0have AT1 instruments that=C2=A0<em>convert in=
to stock=C2=A0</em>when the bank runs into trouble, instead of=C2=A0<em>bei=
ng written down to zero</em>. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/32789269.290422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMTkvZmFzdGVyLW9wdGlvbnMtYXJlLW1vcmUtZnVuP2NtcGlkPUJ=
CRDA5MjEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dG=
VyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkyMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cC69f8064f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> talked the other day</a> about how UBS is going o=
ut to market more AT1 instruments (to replace the zeroed Credit Suisse ones=
!), and to make this more palatable it is considering =E2=80=9Creplacing UB=
S=E2=80=99s AT1 bonds, which are designed to be written down in the event t=
he bank runs into trouble, with versions of the security that would be conv=
erted into equity.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Probably doing that to the old Credit Suisse A=
T1s, retroactively, would be rough justice? Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s shareho=
lders got, I don=E2=80=99t know, depends how you count, somewhere between 1=
 and 40 cents on the dollar for their shares. (The agreed CHF 0.76 price wa=
s =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3278926=
9.290422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMj=
AvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS11YnMtdGFrZW92ZXItaG93LWEtMTY2LXllYXItb2xkLWJhbmstY29sb=
