<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a financial journalist, and a sourc=
e at an investment bank calls you up and says =E2=80=9Chey hot tip, Consoli=
dated Widgets is in advanced talks to acquire Amalgamated Sprockets,=E2=80=
=9D and you call your other sources and the tip checks out, and you write a=
n article saying =E2=80=9CConsolidated in Advanced Talks To Buy Amalgamated=
,=E2=80=9D Amalgamated=E2=80=99s stock will almost certainly shoot up when =
you publish it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could take advantage of this. After you wr=
ite the article, when you send it to your editor, before you hit publish, y=
ou could go to your brokerage account and buy 100 shares of Amalgamated to =
profit when the news is published. No,=C2=A0come on, obviously you can=E2=
=80=99t do that! You will get fired, and you will get ignominiously drummed=
 out of journalism for this breach of ethics, and also you will get extreme=
ly arrested for insider trading. It is a bit of an=C2=A0<em>odd=C2=A0</em>s=
ort of insider trading,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; =
background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> but I think journalists and prosecutors and judges all share an unders=
tanding that it <em>is </em>insider trading, and illegal. (None of this is =
legal or journalism ethics advice.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are more nuanced cases. (If you call you=
r brother-in-law and tell him to trade before your article is published: ba=
d. If you call a third source to check the story, and that source is an inv=
estment banker not involved in the deal, and he says =E2=80=9Chmm dunno abo=
ut that but you=E2=80=99re probably right=E2=80=9D and then buys some Amalg=
amated: I dunno!) But this is a thing that is known, and media organization=
s have rules and ethics guidelines about it, and also the law of insider tr=
ading in securities markets is pretty well developed so there=E2=80=99s a l=
ot of law on it too.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile in sports gambling <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32789269.290422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3N=
qLmNvbS9zcG9ydHMvam91cm5hbGlzdHMtaW5zaWRlLWluZm9ybWF0aW9uLWdhbWJsaW5nLTRlNT=
YwYmM2P21vZD1ocF9saXN0Y19wb3Mz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6da9c64e" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
who knows, man, who knows</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[There is] a potential landmine journalists no=
w face amid the boom of legal sports betting around the country, given thei=
r access to inside information and their ability to affect gambling markets=
. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Athletes and team employees are prohibited fro=
m betting on the league they=E2=80=99re part of. The reason for this rule i=
s obvious: They have access to inside information and have the ability to i=
nfluence the outcomes of events. In some jurisdictions, athletes betting on=
 games they are participating in is a crime.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Journalists frequently know about important de=
velopments like injuries before the general public and are often responsibl=
e for determining who wins awards and makes the Hall of Fame=E2=80=94result=
s that people can bet on.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are a lot fewer rules governing jour=
nalists=E2=80=99 gambling activities. While some media outlets ban their jo=
urnalists from betting on the sports they cover, many have no guidelines at=
 all. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe most pressing ethical question fa=
cing sports journalism over the next couple of years is codifying gambling =
rules,=E2=80=9D said Brian Moritz, a professor at St. Bonaventure Universit=
y who studies the practice of sports journalism.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not, I think,=C2=A0<em>mainly=C2=A0</e=
m>a journalism question. The broader issue is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sports gambling in the US was once mo=
stly illegal; not a lot of people did it, and insider trading was either to=
lerated (gambling was illegal anyway, go ahead and use inside information!)=
 or, like, not tolerated, but <em>by the mob</em>, so there was not a robus=
t body of written regulation.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now =
sports gambling in the US is broadly legal and marketed to retail gamblers,=
 so there is a lot more interest in making it =E2=80=9Cfair=E2=80=9D and a =
=E2=80=9Clevel playing field=E2=80=9D and all the things that people have s=
aid about insider trading in the stock market for decades.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But the rules are not really clear and standardize=
d yet.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I just look forward to the US sports gambling =
market becoming=C2=A0increasingly like the US securities markets, with a lo=
t of rules and enforcement devoted to inside information. I suspect a lot o=
f the rules will be taken from securities markets. The securities markets h=
ave a lot of experience with this.</p>
