e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> we discussed</a> a cor=
porate compliance dilemma, which is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sometimes companies do aggressive thin=
gs.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They do not want anyone saying=
 anything embarrassing about those things in email: If you are doing an agg=
ressive thing, you want to characterize it very carefully in all of your wr=
itten descriptions. You do not want to create bad evidence for regulators t=
o second-guess what you did.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Peopl=
e will mess that up.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The companies=
 will want to train people not to mess up; they will want to tell them thin=
gs like =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t talk about =E2=80=98crushing the competition=
=E2=80=99 in email.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But t=
hat training=C2=A0<em>itself=C2=A0</em>creates bad evidence: Now the regula=
tors have the slide you showed everyone saying =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t talk =
about =E2=80=98crushing the competition=E2=80=99 in email,=E2=80=9D which s=
uggests that you are going around crushing the competition with a guilty co=
nscience.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I proposed that the solution was to separate t=
he aggressive acts from the training. =E2=80=9CReally this stuff should be =
taught in college,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cso that every company ca=
n wash its hands of it.=E2=80=9D Colleges tell future corporate employees w=
hat not to put in email, so the corporations can do aggressive stuff withou=
t creating bad evidence, and without having to create their own =E2=80=9Cdo=
n=E2=80=99t create bad evidence=E2=80=9D training materials that will thems=
elves be bad evidence.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I really do think that this sort of separation=
 is a good solution, but of course I was kidding about doing it in college.=
 Nobody remembers college; it would never work.<a class=3D"footnote-index" =
href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: =
inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a> A reader emailed me with a Straussian reading of my column:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What if instead of giving instructions, compan=
ies hired Blooomberg L.P. to deliver weekly digests of Money Stuff to all e=
mployees, just for fun. Employees would learn a lot of useful stuff but tha=
t would be just from a funny journalist. You could even put stuff about Elo=
n Musk and the hedge fund that is being taken over, just to disguise the tr=
ue purpose.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh. Is Money Stuff ALREADY sponsored by Apollo=
, Bloomberg, and big Wall Street and big law to help with the education of =
the white collar public? Seems likely.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, no, none of that is explicitly what is=
 going on here. And yet!</p>
